  note top of Component
    A component is a structural grouping primitive used to present and manage
    internal architecture.

    Components do not necessarily expose interfaces to the outside of the
    system.

    **Systemic Semantics**:
    - A component groups structural and behavioral primitives to provide a
      manageable internal architecture view of a system.
    - A component is not required to align with an external boundary; it may be
      entirely internal.

    **Attribute Semantics**:
    - "name": Human-readable semantic identifier.
    - "functions": Functions allocated to / realized by the component.
    - "mechanisms": Mechanisms belonging to the component.
    - "interfaces": Interfaces regrouped by the component (may be internal or
      external).
    - "interactions": Interactions in which the component participates.

    **Derivation Rules**:
    - "interfaces" MAY be computed from mechanisms grouped by the component.
    - "interactions" MAY be computed from:
      - interactions carried by channels of those interfaces, and/or
      - interactions whose effector/receptor is owned by those mechanisms.

    **Consistency Rules**:
    - "name" MUST be maximum 80 characters long.
    - "name" MUST be unique among all components of the same system.
  end note

